5000|$|In 2004, Defense Department and {{military}} service branches began publishing directives, messages, and orders, specifying that <b>the</b> Global <b>War</b> <b>on</b> <b>Terrorism</b> Service Medal would be awarded {{not only for}} direct participation in specific operations, but also to any personnel who performed support duty of an anti-terrorism operation but did not directly participate. [...] The phrase [...] "support" [...] was further defined as any administrative, logistics, planning, operational, technical, or readiness activity, which provides support to an operation of <b>the</b> Global <b>War</b> <b>on</b> <b>Terrorism.</b> As {{a result of this}} blanket term, <b>the</b> Global <b>War</b> <b>on</b> <b>Terrorism</b> Service Medal became an eligible award for most personnel of the United States Armed Forces who performed service after 11 September 2001 through March 2004.|$|R
